```java
public class Odev04 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int n = 5;
        int count = 1;

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            int num = count;
            for (int j = 1; j <= i; j++) {
                System.out.print(num + " ");
                num += n - j;
            }
            System.out.println();
            count++;
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, we have an outer loop that iterates from 1 to `n` (which is 5 in this case) to control the number of rows. Inside the outer loop, we have an inner loop that iterates from 1 to the current row number (`i`) to control the number of elements in each row.

We use the `count` variable to keep track of the starting number for each row. In each iteration of the inner loop, we print the current number (`num`) followed by a space. Then, we update the `num` value by adding `n - j` to it, where `j` is the current iteration of the inner loop.

After printing each row, we increment the `count` variable to get the starting number for the next row.

This code will produce the desired output:

```
1 
2 6 
3 7 10 
4 8 11 13 
5 9 12 14 15 
